Regression and Model Validation (week 2)

This week we first learn how to do data wrangling to get the relevant dataset so we can further analyse the learning2014 survey. We then learn how to read the summary of the multiple regression model and conduct analysis on the model validity.

2. Graphical overview

The graphical overview shows summaries of the variables in the data.

There are aprroximately double the amount of female students than male students. Most of the students are under 30 years old. And attitude seems to correlate with points.

3. Multiple regression model - with three explanatory variables

Here I have chosen attitude, strategic learning and deep learning as my three explanatory variables, and exam points as the target variable. The summary as follow:

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude + stra + deep, data = learning2014)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -17.5239  -3.4276   0.5474   3.8220  11.5112 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  11.3915     3.4077   3.343  0.00103 ** 
## attitude      3.5254     0.5683   6.203 4.44e-09 ***
## stra          0.9621     0.5367   1.793  0.07489 .  
## deep         -0.7492     0.7507  -0.998  0.31974    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.289 on 162 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2097, Adjusted R-squared:  0.195 
## F-statistic: 14.33 on 3 and 162 DF,  p-value: 2.521e-08

The above summary shows that the multiple regression equation to be around

points = 11.39 + 3.53(attitude) + 0.96(stra) - 0.75(deep)

  • if the value attitude increase by one, points will increase by 3.53 (if other variables stay the same), and so on. When all three explanatory variables are 0, points is predicted to be 11.39.(This may be because we have excluded points=0)
  • From F test for overall significance, we can conclude that at least one explanatory variable affects ‘points’.
  • The t test shows that there is evidence that ‘attitude’ affects ‘points’, however, it is also quite clear that ‘deep’ has no linear relationship with ‘points’.

4. Multiple regression model - remove deep from the previous model

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude + stra, data = learning2014)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -17.6436  -3.3113   0.5575   3.7928  10.9295 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)   8.9729     2.3959   3.745  0.00025 ***
## attitude      3.4658     0.5652   6.132 6.31e-09 ***
## stra          0.9137     0.5345   1.709  0.08927 .  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.289 on 163 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2048, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1951 
## F-statistic: 20.99 on 2 and 163 DF,  p-value: 7.734e-09

The new summary shows that the regression equation at about

points = 8.97 + 3.47(attitude) + 0.91(stra)

  • Both the explanatory variables have positive affects on the target variable.
  • Multiple R-squared here indicates that 20.5% of the variation in points is explained by the variation in attitude and stra.

5. Model validation

The linear regression model assumes that:

  • Errors are normally distributed.
  • Errors are not correlated.
  • Errors have constant variance.
  • The size of a given error does not depend on the explanatory variables

  • The Residuals vs Fitted values plot here has no pattern, which supports the assumption of constant variance of errors and the size of the errors do not depend on the explanatory variables.

  • The Normal QQ plot here shows that a resonable fit with the line, which means the errors are normally distributed. However, our model is less suitable in the both ends of values.

  • The Residuals vs Leverage plot can measure how much impact a single observation has on the model. Here it is quite scattered, but all are withen 0.06, which means no outliers. (We have already eliminate the observations where points = 0)

6. Conclusion

Attitude has a linear relationship with exam points, but other variables do not have statistically significant relationship with points. What we can do is to find the simple linear regression where attitude is the explanatory variable and use the model to do points predictions in the future.

2. Explore relationships between alcohol consumption and other variables

Here I have chosen 4 variables and with each of them, the following are my hypotheses based on personal experience. I am eager to know if my assumptions are true or not.

  • Students who have better grades in the final drink less alcohol. (G3)
  • Students who have more school absences drinks more. (absences)
  • Students with more freetimes will consume more alcohol.(freetime)
  • Those who are in a relationship will drink more. (romantic)
# initialize a plot of high_use and G3
g1 <- ggplot(alc, aes(x = high_use, y = G3, col=sex)) + geom_boxplot() + ylab('final grade') + xlab('high_use')
# define the plot as a boxplot and draw it
g1 + geom_boxplot() + ylab("grade")+ ggtitle("Student final grades by alcohol consumption and sex")

Graph 1 does not seem to support my assumption perfectly. Grade and alcohol consumption are not correlated within the girls group, however, boys who drink more tend to have poorer grades.

# initialise a plot of high_use and absences
g2 <- ggplot(alc, aes(x= high_use, y = absences, col = sex))
# define the plot as a boxplot and draw it
g2 +geom_boxplot() + ggtitle("Student absences by alcohol consumption and sex")

Graph 2 seems to support my assumption that students who were absence from school more times will drink more.

Graph 3 (although this graph may be hard to read), seems to support my hypothesis. There is a higher percentage of high_use when there is more freetime.

Graph 4 does not support my hypothesis. It even looks like the opposite of my assumption. There is a bigger percentage of “high_use” within the people who is not in a relationship.

The model summary shows that my first and forth hypothesis are wrong. Final grades nor being in a relationship have statistical significances on alcohol consumption. We cannot use them to do predictions.

# define a loss function (mean prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

# call loss_func to compute the average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2774869

5. Conclusion

The four initial hypotheses I have come up with are not convincing after performing analysis with logistic regression. Therefore the variables I have selected are not good predictors when it comes to predicting high alcohol use except for “absences”.

Clustering and Classification (week 4)

This week we will look at the dataset, “Boston”, which already exists inside R, and perform clustering and classification on the data. Also, data wrangling for next week deals with two datasets, “Human development” and “Gender inequality”.

1. Data wrangling for next week

you can see it in my github: https://github.com/tzsu/IODS-project/blob/master/data/create_human.R

2. Analysis

1. about the data: Housing Values in Suburbs of Boston

It is from two sources

    1. Harrison, D. and Rubinfeld, D.L. (1978) Hedonic prices and the demand for clean air. J. Environ. Economics and Management 5, 81–102.
    1. Belsley D.A., Kuh, E. and Welsch, R.E. (1980) Regression Diagnostics. Identifying Influential Data and Sources of Collinearity. New York: Wiley.

The Boston data frame has 506 observations and 14 variables. The following are the variables:

  • crim - per capita crime rate by town
  • zn - proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft
  • indus - proportion of non-retail business acres per town
  • chas - Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)
  • nox - nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million)
  • rm - average number of rooms per dwelling
  • age - proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940
  • dis - weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres
  • rad - index of accessibility to radial highways
  • tax - full-value property-tax rate per $10,000
  • ptratio - pupil-teacher ratio by town
  • black - 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town
  • lstat - lower status of the population (%)
  • medv - median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s

4. Fitting the linear discriminant analysis on the train set. Use the categorical crime rate as the target variable and all the other variables in the dataset as predictor variables.

# linear discriminant analysis
lda.fit <- lda(crime~., data = train)
# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}
# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

Look at the LDA (bi)plot.

# plot the lda results
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 3)

2. Analysis

1. About the Human data:

The Human data includes two data sets: “Human development” and “Gender inequality”. We keep only the countries in both data sets, and exclude rows with missing values . After combining some variables and excluding some, the Human data we will use for performing analysis has 155 observations and the folowing 8 variables:

the 8 variables:

  • ratioedu2.fm = Share of female population with secondary education over(/) share of male population with secondary education
  • ratiolab.fm = Share of female population that participates in labour force over(/) share of male population that participates in labour force
  • exp.y.edu = Expected years of schooling
  • life.exp = Life expectancy at birth
  • gni.cap = Gross national income per capita
  • mmr = Maternal mortality ratio
  • ad.b.r = Adolescent birth rate
  • par% = population with at least some secondary education
